title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message:
Had a liquid spill exactly on C7500 and C7503.

Since C7500 is 8v and C7503 is 5v, is it fair to guess a dead U7501?

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message: Also check clock / ROM area ( U6100, Y1905, U1900 ), very common for 3437/00165 to suffer issues there due to liquid ingress (or even just literal bugs), especially if it got as far in on the board as C7500.

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message: You are guessing without taking any measurements?

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message:
There is no 3v3_s5 why are we looking at U8020? This is something around the TPS51980 or a short on 3v3_s5.

Check traces around U7501 and/or replace.

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message:
[QUOTE="dukefawks, post: 34814"]There is no 3v3_s5 why are we looking at U8020? [/QUOTE]

Not specifically U8020, but 3v3SUS_EN.

[quote]
This is something around the TPS51980 or a short on 3v3_s5.

Check traces around U7501 and/or replace.[/QUOTE]

The traces around U7501 are horrible but seem to beep out ok.

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message: Replace 7501 and check traces while it's off, especially pin 23.

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message: ::23 has continuity to C7540 et al, but ::24 has nothing to Q7560.

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message:
Got continuity back. Replaced u7501 with a new one.

PP5v_S5 @C7505 is 0.9v now. Crappy soldering maybe?

title: 820-3437 - No power, green/orange light ok.
message: I have no idea, you have your eyes on it. This problem is around U7501 for sure.
